3141	  The isomorphism \(H^0(U, -) \cong \Gamma(U, -)\) of Lemma~\ref{lem:absolute_cohomology_zero} is
3142	  natural in the coefficient sheaf: for a morphism \(g : \mathcal{F}_1 \to \mathcal{F}_2\) in
3143	  \(X.\mathrm{Modules}\) the square
3144	  \[
3145	    \begin{array}{ccc}
3146	      H^0(U, \mathcal{F}_1) & \longrightarrow & H^0(U, \mathcal{F}_2)\\
3147	      \cong\downarrow & & \downarrow\cong\\
3148	      \Gamma(U, \mathcal{F}_1) & \xrightarrow{\;g_U\;} & \Gamma(U, \mathcal{F}_2)
3149	    \end{array}
3150	  \]
3151	  commutes, where the top arrow is \(H^0(U, g)\), the functorial action of \(g\) on
3152	  \(\operatorname{Ext}^0\) in the second variable, and the bottom arrow is the sections map
3153	  \(g_U = g(U)\).
3154	\end{lemma}
3155	\begin{proof}
3156	  \uses{lem:absolute_cohomology_zero, lem:jshriek_corepr}
3157	  Under the degree-zero Ext comparison, post-composition by the degree-zero Ext class of \(g\)
3158	  corresponds to post-composition by \(g\) in \(\operatorname{Hom}_{X.\mathrm{Modules}}(j_!
3159	  \mathcal{O}_U, -)\); under the corepresentability isomorphism of Lemma~\ref{lem:jshriek_corepr}
3160	  (which is natural in the second variable, being a composite of the sheafification adjunction and
3161	  the free–Yoneda evaluation, both natural), this in turn corresponds to applying \(g\) on sections
3162	  over \(U\), i.e. \(g_U\). Hence the square commutes. In particular, when \(g_U\) is surjective so
3163	  is \(H^0(U, g)\) — the transfer used by the surjectivity step of
3164	  Lemma~\ref{lem:absolute_cohomology_one_vanishing}.
3165	\end{proof}
